thinsp;ppb, respectively (changes quoted here are for the entire 2015–2055 time period; uncertainty represents the 95\&thinsp;\% confidence interval), over global land surfaces, with larger reductions in some regions including south and southeast Asia. Non-methane {NTCF} mitigation, however, leads to additional climate change due to the removal of aerosol which causes a net warming effect, including global mean surface temperature and precipitation increases of {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}0.25±0.12{\textless}/span{\textgreater}\&thinsp;K and {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}0.03±0.012{\textless}/span{\textgreater}\&thinsp;mm\&thinsp;d{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{−1}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}, respectively. Similarly, increases in extreme weather indices, including the hottest and wettest days, also occur. Regionally, the largest warming and wetting occurs over Asia, including central and north Asia ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}0.66±0.20{\textless}/span{\textgreater}\&thinsp;K and {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}0.03±0.02{\textless}/span{\textgreater}\&thinsp;mm\&thinsp;d{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{−1}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}), south Asia ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}0.47±0.16{\textless}/span{\textgreater}\&thinsp;K and {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}0.17±0.09{\textless}/span{\textgreater}\&thinsp;mm\&thinsp;d{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{−1}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}), and east Asia ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}0.46±0.20{\textless}/span{\textgreater}\&thinsp;K and {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}0.15±0.06{\textless}/span{\textgreater}\&thinsp;mm\&thinsp;d{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{−1}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}). Relatively large warming and wetting of the Arctic also occur at {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}0.59±0.36{\textless}/span{\textgreater}\&thinsp;K and {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}0.04±0.02{\textless}/span{\textgreater}\&thinsp;mm\&thinsp;d{\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}$^{\textrm{−1}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}, respectively. Similar surface warming occurs in model simulations with aerosol-only mitigation, implying weak cooling due to ozone reductions. Our findings suggest that future policies that aggressively target non-methane {NTCF} reductions will improve air quality but will lead to additional surface warming, particularly in Asia and the Arctic. Policies that address other {NTCFs} including methane, as well as carbon dioxide emissions, must also be adopted to meet climate mitigation goals.{\textless}/p{\textgreater}},
