	abstract = {{\textless}p{\textgreater}{\textless}strong{\textgreater}Abstract.{\textless}/strong{\textgreater} This study quantifies future changes in tropospheric ozone ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}O$_{\textrm{3}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}) using a simple parameterisation of source–receptor relationships based on simulations from a range of models participating in the Task Force on Hemispheric Transport of Air Pollutants ({TF}-{HTAP}) experiments. Surface and tropospheric {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}O$_{\textrm{3}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} changes are calculated globally and across 16 regions from perturbations in precursor emissions ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}{NO}$_{\textrm{\textit{x}}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}, {CO}, volatile organic compounds – {VOCs}) and methane ({\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}{CH}$_{\textrm{4}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater}) abundance only, neglecting any impact from climate change. A source attribution is provided for each source region along with an estimate of uncertainty based on the spread of the results from the models. Tests against model simulations using the Hadley Centre Global Environment Model version 2 – Earth system configuration ({HadGEM}2-{ES}) confirm that the approaches used within the parameterisation perform well for most regions. The {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}O$_{\textrm{3}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} response to changes in {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}{CH}$_{\textrm{4}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} abundance is slightly larger in the {TF}-{HTAP} Phase 2 than in the {TF}-{HTAP} Phase 1 assessment (2010) and provides further evidence that controlling {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}{CH}$_{\textrm{4}}${\textless}/span{\textgreater} is important for limiting future {\textless}span class="inline-formula"{\textgreater}O$_{\textrm{3}}${\textl